    {
      "id": "/page/0/Text/12",
      "block_type": "Text",
      "html": "<p block-type=\"Text\">The number of assets in Mountain Range options generally ranges from a low of 4 or 5 to a high of about 20. Owing to their complex payoff and path-dependency, idiosyncratic characteristics of each asset need to be taken into account. Hence one cannot assume homogeneity of assets for neither small nor large baskets, making any closed-form approximation (especially in light of path dependence) intractable. Consequently, Mountain Range options, even the non-path-dependent Atlas options, are calculated using Monte Carlo simulation [1]. Monte Carlo methods, especially for high-dimensional payoffs with large number of assets, are slow to converge, and usually one or more variance-reduction techniques are employed. This problem is exacerbated further when calculating first and second order Greeks.</p>",
      "page": 375,
